Here's how to save and restore draft text using Window lifecycle events:

**1. Create a custom `Window` subclass in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Stopped += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Save draft when app backgrounds
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
            {
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", page.ViewModel.DraftText);
            }
        };

        window.Resumed += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Restore draft when app returns
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
            {
                page.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
            }
        };

        window.Destroying += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
            {
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", page.ViewModel.DraftText);
            }
        };

        return window;
    }
}
```

**2. Your ViewModel:**

```csharp
public partial class NoteViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _draftText = string.Empty;

    public NoteViewModel()
    {
        // Restore on first load too
        DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    [RelayCommand]
    private void SaveNote()
    {
        // Persist final note, then clear draft
        Preferences.Remove("draft_text");
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

| Concern | Approach |
|---------|----------|
| Save trigger | `Stopped` (app backgrounded) |
| Restore trigger | `Resumed` (app foregrounded after stop) |
| Android back button | Also save in `Destroying` |
| Storage | `Preferences` â€” fast, synchronous, no ANR risk |
| First launch | `Resumed` does **not** fire â€” restore in the constructor |

Keep lifecycle handlers under 1â€“2 seconds to avoid ANR on Android or watchdog kills on iOS. `Preferences` is ideal for small text; for larger documents, use `File.WriteAllTextAsync` to a known path instead.
